
---

Stage 1 — Local AI Assistant (Foundation)

Overview

Stage 1 focused on building a fully local, private AI assistant with:

local LLM inference

remote access via VPN

Telegram-based interaction

persistent memory and sessions

basic system tooling


The goal started as "run a local model" and quickly moved onto:

“usable, persistent, remote AI assistant with real utility”


---

Architecture

Core components:

Ollama (local LLM runtime)

Open WebUI (LLM web interface)

Tailscale (mesh VPN)

python-telegram-bot (Telegram integration)


Flow:

Telegram → bot.py → state.py → ollama_client.py → Ollama → Model
↓
tools.py


---

Stage 1 Deliverables

1. Local LLM Deployment

Installed and configured Ollama

Pulled and tested multiple models:

general models (e.g. LLaMA, Qwen)

coding models (e.g. Qwen coder)


Exposed local API: http://127.0.0.1:11434



---

2. Web UI Integration

Deployed Open WebUI via Docker

Connected to Ollama backend

Enabled:

browser-based chat

system prompts

multi-conversation UI



Acts as the primary desktop interface.


---

3. Secure Remote Access

Configured Tailscale VPN

Enabled private access to:

Web UI

server services

bot backend



No public port exposure required.


---

4. Telegram Bot Interface

Built custom Telegram bot using python-telegram-bot

Runs as a systemd service:


telegram-ollama-bot.service

Features:

mobile access to local AI

persistent connection

controlled access via chat ID



---

5. Streaming Responses

Implemented streaming from Ollama API

Replaced “wait → full reply” with:

progressive message updates

improved responsiveness




---

6. Session System (Multi-Conversation Support)

Telegram lacks native conversation threads, so sessions were introduced:

Commands:

/session <name>
/sessions
/delsession <name>

Each session:

has independent memory

can use different models



---

7. Persistent Memory

Chat history stored per session:


/data/projects/telegram-bot/memory/<chat_id>/<session>.json

Automatically:

loaded on access

trimmed to max history

saved after each interaction



Also persisted:

<chat_id>_current_session.txt


---

8. Model Management

Commands:

/models
/setmodel <model>
/model

Features:

dynamic model switching

per-session model assignment

model list pulled from Ollama



---

9. Tooling System (Phase 1)

Manual tools:

/uptime
/disk
/sysinfo
/run <command>

Provides:

system visibility

basic remote control



---

10. Automatic Tool Usage (Basic)

Implemented keyword-based routing:

Examples:

“how long has the server been up” → uptime tool

“disk space” → disk tool


Flow:

user message → tool detection → tool execution → AI explanation


---

11. Codebase Refactor

Split monolithic bot into modular structure:

bot.py            → Telegram handlers
state.py          → sessions + memory
ollama_client.py  → API interaction
tools.py          → system utilities
config.py         → environment/config

Benefits:

easier maintenance

reduced duplication bugs

cleaner extension for future features



---

Stage 1 Outcomes

By the end of Stage 1, the system provides:

private, local AI assistant

persistent multi-session conversations

remote access via Telegram

real-time streaming responses

basic system introspection tools

modular, extensible codebase

---

Known Limitations

Tool routing is keyword-based (not true intent detection)

/run command is broad and not fully restricted

Bot runs under primary user (no privilege separation yet)

No automated monitoring or alerting

No structured tool permission system

No Git-based version control at initial stage



---

Stage 2 Preview

Stage 2 will focus on:

security hardening (dedicated user, restricted permissions)

safe system control (reboot, shutdown, firewall)

monitoring and alerting

structured tool framework

GitHub integration and backup



---

Summary

Stage 1 established the core platform:

a locally hosted, persistent, remotely accessible AI assistant with system awareness

The foundation is now stable enough to safely expand into controlled automation and operational tooling in Stage 2.
